<node TEXT="sh : for investig + against instruction-reliance" LOCALIZED_STYLE_REF="default" ID="ID_1209297072" CREATED="1401570585097" MODIFIED="1449375466066">
<node TEXT="Teachers in music are parasites." ID="ID_1694822527" CREATED="1401570589039" MODIFIED="1401570589039"/>
<node TEXT="Learn ear training. It will let you to perceive in audio anything that you would otherwise rely on a teacher to detect. Practica Musica is a piece of software, $100 to students (as of 2005), with infinite patience and zero marginal cost, on which you can train your ear (it&apos;s like learning to name colors; you&apos;ve been hearing them the whole time but having words for them makes working with them much easier) more effectively than with a human partner. No human should need to be physically present to quiz another; that work can be automated." ID="ID_691649024" CREATED="1401570589039" MODIFIED="1401570589039"/>
<node TEXT="Once you have ear trained you will be able to recognize and label the things you hear. It&apos;s a small step from there to being able to reproduce them on an instrument." ID="ID_1259207576" CREATED="1401570589039" MODIFIED="1401570589039"/>
<node TEXT="Study music theory, concurrently with or after ear training. You probably don&apos;t even need to spend any money on books, just look around online. Ear training will make music theory meaningful and operationalizable. As you read, be skeptical of the value of what you&apos;re reading. Generally, the lists are useful (like &quot;Here are all the scales satisfying certian conditions&quot;) while the imperatives (like &quot;Try not to move two voices in the same direction by the same amount&quot;) are worth being aware of but not worth investing a lot of effort into." ID="ID_1469154133" CREATED="1401570589041" MODIFIED="1401570589041"/>
<node TEXT="Do your own math. Once you understand enough music theory to come up with mathematical problems (e.g. &quot;What families of scales have I not studied?&quot;), working on your own problems will, if you&apos;re like me, soon feel more useful than reading more of someone else&apos;s music theory." ID="ID_1762695973" CREATED="1401570589042" MODIFIED="1401570589042"/>
<node TEXT="Music notation is dumb as dogshit. Devise and use your own numerical language(s) instead of the irregular, arithmetic-resistant system of letters and modifiers that cripples so many musicians." ID="ID_1359005061" CREATED="1401570589043" MODIFIED="1401570589043"/>
<node TEXT="For biomechanics, do some reading about best practices, and study your own biology as you try things out. I am skeptical of any fixed method of execution; I believe it should evolve as one&apos;s body changes in perpetuity. In biomechanics particularly, what you feel is more important than what any instructor could tell you." ID="ID_261420480" CREATED="1401570589045" MODIFIED="1401570589045"/>
<node TEXT="Play a lot. Play with others as soon and as often as you are able." ID="ID_1539070444" CREATED="1401570589046" MODIFIED="1401570589046"/>
<node TEXT="The production function on these things is convex or something -- each project helps the others, so it&apos;s easier to do them all than to specialize in any one of them." ID="ID_668059681" CREATED="1401570589047" MODIFIED="1401570589047"/>
</node>
